To me. Christmas means making memories. Together. As a family. Growing up it was easy. We all lived in one house. Would wake up together on Christmas morning. Open gifts. Eat Italian food. Laugh. And enjoy. As we grew up. The distance became greater. Life became different. Schedules became busier. Christmas became different. We haven’t been home on Christmas. As a family. In years. But this year. With mom guiding us. We did it. Together. As a family. Under one roof. Again. New memories made. Traditions continue.

I am a day late on posting. I wanted to soak in the first day of the new year. Be more present. To sit back and think about how amazing 2022 was. I’m not much of a “New Year’s resolution” type, but more of a “set goals and crush em” type. I set out into 2022 with a lot of personal goals. A lot of professional goals. A lot of growth goals. I can honestly say I surpassed what I thought I could accomplish. In just 12 months time. Amazing. It will be a year I will always remember. Time to write down my goals for 2023 and begin the process again.  Happy New Year and best wishes on crushing your own goals!

When I started my radio career in back in 2001, I thought it would be a fun career. One that beat clocking in to a boring job. One that would allow me opportunities to do things that dreams are made of. One thing I didn’t realize, 22 years ago as a young punk in this business, was how it would allow me to give back. Looking back on all the amazing experiences this career has brought me, I’ve realized that nothing is more important than using my voice for the good of a community! I was honored over a decade ago to be asked to MC the St Baldricks Shave-A-Thon to raise money for childhood cancer research. I am even more honored that years later they still invite me back! Congrats to Jake, Gil, Michaela and the whole crew for your biggest one yet! 🙌🏼❤️🙏🏻

The quote “The comeback is always stronger than the setback” was on my mind the past couple months. It motivated me to get through this chapter.  What originally was thought to have been laryngitis turned out to be a polyp on my vocal cord. For someone that has never been a fan of going to doctors, hearing the word “surgery” was not something that sat easy with me. Mom flew in, Courtney took the day off from work, Luna stayed by my side, friends let me know they had my back, listeners sent their well wishes. From surgery to vocal rest to healing, WE did it. Today I got up, dusted myself off, and got back on the air! I’ll be honest, I was proud of myself. I battled back. I had my doubts. I had my fears. I had a lot of uncertainties when this vocal issue started. But I stayed the course, stayed positive, and bounced back! Thank you to everyone that was there for me through this. I am not sure I could have done it without you! Time to refocus, reenergize, and get back to doing what I love to do! 🙏🏼❤️🙌🏼
•
The last picture is the before and after if my vocal cord. If you have a weak stomach don’t look at it 🫣
•
#positivity #Bounceback #thankful

On stage. Mic in hand. Hosting a sold out event. A few months ago I wasn’t sure if I was going to be able to do this again. It’s the mental part for me. What if I try and my voice isn’t strong enough? What if I try and the next day I’m in pain? What if I try and the next day I’m back in the hospital? All these “what ifs” disappeared today. Woke up with zero pain. A strong voice. And the confidence that I’m BACK! This was the final test. I passed. Such a great feeling! Thank you to @hardrocksd for the love. Thank you to @courtney_jo_ for handling our costumes. Thank you to @theproducerchris for helping host. Thank you to my crew for showing up. Thank you to YOU for following my journey. Together we can accomplish anything!
